position at the RAND Corporation and serving as a powerful consultant to the State Department and Ford Foundation, across the mid-twentieth century. Bessner depicts the critical role Speier played in the shift in American intellectual history in which hundreds of social scientists left their universities and contributed to the creation of an expert-based approach to U.S. foreign relations, in the process establishing close connections between governmental and nongovernmental organizations. As Bessner writes: to understand the rise of the defense intellectual, we must understand Hans Speier.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDiplomatic relations. 0aExilesxBiographyxGermany. 0aExileszGermanyvBiography. 0aExiles. 0aIntellectual life. 0aNational securityxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aNational securityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational security. 0aSociologistsxBiographyxGermany. 0aSociologistsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aSociologistszGermanyvBiography. 0aSociologistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aSociologists. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History.  aexpertise, foreign relations, RAND corporation, Cold War, propaganda.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics and Social Sciences 2018 Englishz978311060401608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2018z9783110603231oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170939540uhttps://